/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 658.0 Tm (Abstract) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 644.0 Tm (Ectomycorrhizal fungi connect the roots of neighbouring trees into shared hyphal networks) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 630.0 Tm (whose ecological function remains contested. Using a dual isotope labelling scheme in a) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 616.0 Tm (mixed birch-fir stand, we tracked carbon movement between donor and receiver seedlings) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 602.0 Tm (across a growing season. We detected consistent net transfer from shaded receivers' larger) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 588.0 Tm (neighbours, but the magnitude was small relative to each plant's own fixation, and we) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 574.0 Tm (caution against the popular framing of these networks as deliberate resource-sharing) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 560.0 Tm (systems.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 546.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 528.0 Tm (Introduction) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 514.0 Tm (Few ideas in soil science have escaped the laboratory as thoroughly as the notion of a) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 500.0 Tm (forest connected underground by fungal threads. The image of trees feeding their neighbours) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 486.0 Tm (through a fungal network is compelling, but compelling images make for poor controls. This) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 472.0 Tm (study asks a deliberately narrow question: how much carbon actually moves between trees) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 458.0 Tm (through shared mycorrhizae, and under what conditions?) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 444.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 430.0 Tm (We focus on ectomycorrhizal associations in a temperate birch-fir stand, where the two host) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 416.0 Tm (species share compatible fungal partners and where natural light gradients create the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 402.0 Tm (source-sink differences that any transfer hypothesis requires.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 388.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 370.0 Tm (Isotope Labelling Design) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 356.0 Tm (Donor seedlings were pulse-labelled with a heavy carbon isotope delivered to their foliage) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 342.0 Tm (in a sealed chamber, while neighbouring receiver seedlings were left at ambient conditions.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 328.0 Tm (A second, distinguishable label applied to the receivers allowed us to confirm that any) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 314.0 Tm (heavy carbon found in receiver tissue had genuinely crossed from the donor rather than) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 300.0 Tm (arriving by some shared atmospheric route.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 286.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 272.0 Tm (Crucially, half of the receiver seedlings were separated from donors by a fine mesh that) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 258.0 Tm (excluded roots but admitted fungal hyphae, while a control set was separated by a barrier) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 244.0 Tm (that excluded both. Transfer observed in the first group but not the second can be) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 230.0 Tm (attributed to the fungal network rather than to direct root grafting or soil leakage.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 216.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 198.0 Tm (Magnitude and Direction of Transfer) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 184.0 Tm (Net carbon transfer through the hyphal network was real and statistically robust, but) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 170.0 Tm (modest. Receivers acquired on the order of a few percent of their seasonal carbon from donor) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 156.0 Tm (neighbours, with transfer rising when the receiver was deeply shaded and the donor well lit.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 142.0 Tm (Direction followed the source-sink gradient: carbon moved from where it was abundant toward) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 128.0 Tm (where it was scarce.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 114.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 100.0 Tm (This directionality is exactly what passive physical transport would predict. We found no) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 86.0 Tm (evidence that donor trees preferentially supplied kin, nor that the fungus directed carbon) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 72.0 Tm (in any way that served the trees rather than itself. The fungus is better understood as a) Tj
